  "signature": "ed25519:7b3e9f2a1c4d5e6f0a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver version control, regression test suite covering hemolysis-relevant flow regimes, and documented change management process must satisfy MRL 5 SQA requirements (Gradation 4).",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2024 R1) is under formal version control with a documented regression test suite. However, the regression suite does not include rotating machinery cases with blood analog fluids, and the change management log for the hemolysis UDF (user-defined function) lacks formal review signatures for two patch releases applied during the assessment period. Achieved level 3 reflects partial but incomplete SQA coverage for this specific application class."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Order-of-accuracy verification for the hemolysis transport scalar and the momentum equations must be demonstrated on canonical rotating-flow test cases at MRL 5 required level (Gradation 4).",
      "rationale": "Order-of-accuracy testing was performed on a rotating annular Couette flow benchmark and on a simplified impeller passage. Observed order of accuracy for momentum equations is 1.87 (expected 2.0), consistent with boundary discretization effects. The hemolysis scalar transport equation achieved observed order 1.62, below the expected second-order value. The team attributes this to interpolation at the rotating-stationary interface. Formal manufactured solution verification was not completed for the full pump geometry. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence study using at least three systematically refined meshes with GCI estimation for all QoIs at all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "Three systematically refined meshes (8.2M, 22.4M, and 61.1M cells, refinement ratio 1.4) were constructed following ASME V&V 20 guidelines. GCI-estimated discretization uncertainty for NIH predictions ranges from 2.1% to 6.8% across operating points, with the highest uncertainty at the 6000 RPM condition due to thin shear layers near the volute cutwater. All GCI estimates are within the required threshold for Gradation 4. Achieved level 4 — this factor meets its required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must match COU operating conditions within documented tolerance bounds; fluid properties, temperature control, and pump rotational speed must be characterized with uncertainty at Gradation 4.",
      "rationale": "PIV experiments were conducted with a blood-analog fluid (aqueous glycerol, 36% v/v) at 37°C ± 0.5°C. Rotational speed was controlled to ±15 RPM. However, the hemolysis bench tests used porcine blood rather than human blood, introducing species-dependent red cell fragility differences that were not formally characterized. Inlet flow rate uncertainty was ±4.2% (k=2), slightly exceeding the Gradation 4 threshold of ±3%. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E_rel or validation uncertainty) must demonstrate agreement within expanded validation uncertainty at all five operating points for the primary QoI (NIH), satisfying Gradation 5 requirements for MRL 5.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed using the validation metric defined in ASME V&V 20. Agreement within expanded validation uncertainty (k=2) was achieved at two of five operating points for the primary QoI (NIH). At the remaining three operating points, CFD predictions fall outside the expanded validation uncertainty interval: the 4500 RPM / 5 L/min point shows 18% relative error, the 5250 RPM / 4 L/min point shows 21% relative error, and the 6000 RPM / 3 L/min point shows 31% relative error. The team notes that all three discrepant predictions are conservative (CFD overpredicts hemolysis), which they argue is protective for patient safety. Achieved level 2 — significantly below the required level 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation QoIs must directly correspond to the COU decision QoIs (absolute NIH values) with no surrogate substitution, at Gradation 4.",
      "rationale": "The primary validation QoI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) is identical to the COU decision QoI. No surrogate quantities were substituted. Secondary QoIs (velocity fields, wall shear stress distributions) support mechanistic understanding but are not used as proxies for the hemolysis decision. Achieved level 4 — this factor meets its required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must use the same pump geometry, fluid, and operating range as the COU, or differences must be formally bridged with documented similarity arguments at Gradation 4.",
      "rationale": "Validation used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is identical to the COU geometry. Operating points span the full COU range. However, validation experiments used porcine blood (hemolysis bench) and blood-analog fluid (PIV), while the COU involves human blood. A formal similarity argument was provided for the PIV comparison but was not provided for the species-dependent hemolysis response. This gap limits the achieved level to 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated to solver-independent residual levels for all QoIs; floating-point and round-off error must be characterized at Gradation 3.",
      "rationale": "All simulations were converged to residual levels below 1e-5 for continuity, momentum, and scalar transport equations. Mass imbalance across the rotating-stationary interface was verified to be below 0.01% for all operating points. Double-precision arithmetic was used throughout. Achieved level 3 — meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented simulation plan, independent review of boundary condition setup, and audit trail for all simulation inputs at Gradation 4.",
      "rationale": "A simulation plan was documented prior to execution. Boundary conditions were independently reviewed by a second engineer. However, the audit trail for the hemolysis UDF parameter inputs was reconstructed post-hoc from analyst notes rather than captured prospectively in the simulation management system. One operating point required a boundary condition correction after initial runs, and the re-run rationale was documented informally via email rather than in the formal audit log. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form uncertainty must be quantified and bounded for both the turbulence closure and the hemolysis damage accumulation model at Gradation 5 for MRL 5.",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty was assessed for the turbulence closure (SST k-omega versus RSM comparison at two operating points) and for the hemolysis model (Giersiepen versus Taskin power-law comparison). The turbulence model comparison showed up to 14% difference in NIH predictions at high-speed conditions. The hemolysis model comparison showed up to 28% difference. Formal Bayesian model form uncertainty quantification was not performed; the assessment relied on sensitivity comparisons rather than rigorous probabilistic model form error bounds. This is insufficient for Gradation 5. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters must be characterized with traceable uncertainty distributions; sensitivity analysis must identify dominant inputs at Gradation 4.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification propagated uncertainty in 11 model input parameters including blood viscosity, inlet velocity profile, rotational speed, and hemolysis model coefficients. Sobol sensitivity indices were computed from the 2500-sample ensemble, identifying hemolysis model coefficient C and blood viscosity as the two dominant contributors (combined 67% of output variance). Input uncertainty distributions were derived from literature meta-analysis and device specification tolerances. Achieved level 4 — meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental sample size must be sufficient to characterize biological and run-to-run variability in hemolysis measurements at Gradation 4; statistical power analysis must be documented.",
      "rationale": "Hemolysis bench tests were performed with n=3 replicates per operating point. A post-hoc statistical power analysis determined that n=3 provides 52% power to detect a 15% difference in NIH at alpha=0.05, which is substantially below the 80% power threshold required for Gradation 4. The small sample size results in wide confidence intervals on measured NIH values, which in turn inflate the validation uncertainty and mask potential model discrepancies. A prospective power analysis was not conducted prior to testing. Achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Input parameters used in validation simulations must be demonstrably equivalent to those used in COU simulations; any differences must be formally bridged at Gradation 4.",
      "rationale": "Geometric inputs are identical between validation and COU simulations (same CAD model). Fluid properties differ: validation used porcine blood rheology parameters while COU simulations use human blood rheology from the Quemada model. A bridging argument was provided citing published comparative viscometry data, but the argument does not address species differences in red cell membrane properties relevant to hemolysis susceptibility. Achieved level 3."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou2-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-assessment-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 credibility factors and determined that the aggregated evidence supports acceptance of the CFD model for the stated COU. While individual factor shortfalls were identified — most notably in Output Comparison (achieved 2, required 5), Model Form (achieved 3, required 5), and Test Samples (achieved 2, required 4) — the team judged these shortfalls to be mitigated by the conservative direction of model predictions (CFD systematically overpredicts hemolysis), the robustness of the Monte Carlo UQ framework, and the fact that the 95th-percentile predictions remain below the clinical threshold at four of five operating points. The declared assurance level of Medium reflects the team's holistic confidence in the evidence package. The model is accepted for use in the regulatory submission with the noted limitations documented in the assessment report.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
